Airline On-Time Performance Data Exploration¶

Introduction¶

This dataset reports flights in the USA, including carriers, arrival and departure delays, and reasons for delays, from 1987 to 2008. To hold the analysis, 100K rows of data were randomly selected from each of the datasets of corresponding years. Data Source

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Gather data¶

The data is downloaded from the site: https://community.amstat.org/jointscsg-section/dataexpo/dataexpo2009

As there are separate datasets for each year, it was necessary merge them to get one general one

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The whole dataset is distributed among years each one containing 29 columns and millions of rows.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest in the dataset are the increase/decrease flight trends over the years, also the relationships between delay times, and scheduled hours.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Arrival and Departure Delay columns, as well as date, month, and weekday columns.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, distributions of individual variables were investigated.

Question #1¶

In which month the most number of flights occurred during the period of 1987-2008?

Visualisation¶

In [13]:
# get the mount count
month_count = df['Month'].value_counts().sort_index()
month_labels = month_count.index

# calculate the relative frequency
month_total = month_count.sum()

max_value = month_count.values[0] / month_total

tick_props = np.arange(0, max_value + 0.04, 0.02)
tick_names = ['{:0.2f}'.format(v) for v in tick_props]
In [63]:
import calendar
# get month labels
abbr_month = [calendar.month_abbr[label] for label in month_labels.values]

base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]

# set the figure size
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

# seaborn countplot
sb.countplot(data=df, x="Month", color=base_color, order=month_labels)

plt.title("Number of the US flights in 1987-2008")

# set the custom ticks
plt.yticks(tick_props * month_total, tick_names)
plt.xticks(np.arange(0, 12, 1), abbr_month)

plt.ylabel("Proportion");

Observation¶

It is notable that the number of flights were genuinely close to each other, October containing the most.

Observation¶

Both of the arrival and departure delay values had to be transformed into the logarithmic scale due to the outliers. It looks like some flights had to be postponed for a couple of hours.

It is also apparent that most number of delays were for a minute. Moreover, negative values imply early arrival and delay minutes.

Question #5¶

What is the most common cancellation reason of flights?

Visualisation¶

In [21]:
# figure
plt.figure(figsize=[7, 7])

cancel_codes = df["CancellationCode"].value_counts()

# A = carrier, B = weather, C = NAS, D = security
cancel_labels = ['carrier', 'weather', 'NAS', 'security']

# display percentages on the pie plot
plt.pie(cancel_codes, labels=cancel_labels, startangle=90, counterclock=False, autopct='%1.1f%%',
        explode=(0.1, 0, 0.1, 0.1),
        wedgeprops = {"edgecolor" : "white",
                      'linewidth': 0,
                      'antialiased': True})

# title and labels
plt.title("The US Flight Cancellation Reasons in 1987-2008");

Observation¶

The most common reason for flight cancellation was carrier, the second most common being weather, followed by NAS, and only in a few cases security.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

When the departure and arrival delay minutes were observed, the distributions seemed to lack proper information without proper scaling. Therefore, logarithmic scaling was used multiple times to get more insights. The most common delay or earliness time was 1 minute.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

There were many negative values in the delay time columns which indicated potential earlier arrivals/departures. There were several outliers that exceeded 1000 minutes in both cases. Therefore, changing the axis tick limits also helped.

delay_types = df.melt(id_vars=['Year'],
                      value_vars=['CarrierDelay', 'WeatherDelay', 'NASDelay', 'SecurityDelay', 'LateAircraftDelay'],
                      var_name="delay_type",
                      value_name="delay_minutes")

delay_types['delay_minutes'] = delay_types['delay_minutes'].apply(lambda x: x if x!= 0.0 else np.nan)
delay_types.dropna(inplace=True)
In [57]:
# function to avoid repeating the label names and tick values
def common_attributes():
    plt.title("1987-2008 US flights Time Offset Distribution with Log scaling")
    plt.xlabel("Delay Type")
    plt.ylabel("Earliness Time Offset                     Delay Time Offset in minutes")

    plt.yscale("symlog")

    plt.axhline(0, color='red')

    ytick_values = [-10, -3, -1, 0, 1, 2, 5, 10, 30, 100, 1000, 2400]
    ytick_names = [str(value) for value in ytick_values]

    plt.yticks(ytick_values, ytick_names)

Question #8¶

What is the relationship between the departure and arrival time offsets (earliness and delay)?

Visualisation¶

In [26]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))

sb.regplot(data=df, x='DepDelay', y='ArrDelay', scatter_kws={"alpha": 0.5}, line_kws={"color": "orange"})

plt.title("The 1987-2008 US Flights Departure and Arrival Offset Times Relationship")
plt.xlabel("Departure Offset in minutes")
plt.ylabel("Arrival Offset in minutes");
In [27]:
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 8))

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)

# positive minutes
positive_dep_delay = df["DepDelay"].apply(lambda x: x if x > 0 else np.nan)
positive_arr_delay = df["ArrDelay"].apply(lambda x: x if x > 0 else np.nan)

# regression plot
sb.regplot(x=positive_arr_delay, y=positive_dep_delay, scatter_kws={"alpha": 0.5}, line_kws={"color": "orange"})

# title and labels
plt.title("The 1987-2008 US Flights Departure and Arrival Delay Times Relationship")
plt.xlabel("Departure Delay in minutes")
plt.ylabel("Arrival Delay in minutes")

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)

# negative minutes: early departure & arrival
negative_dep_delay = df["DepDelay"].apply(lambda x: abs(x) if x < 0 else np.nan)
negative_arr_delay = df["ArrDelay"].apply(lambda x: abs(x) if x < 0 else np.nan)

# regression plot
sb.regplot(x=negative_arr_delay, y=negative_dep_delay, scatter_kws={"alpha": 0.5}, line_kws={"color": "orange"})
plt.title("The 1987-2008 US Flights Departure and Arrival Earliness Times Relationship")
plt.xlabel("Departure Earliness in minutes")
plt.ylabel("Arrival Earliness in minutes");

Observation¶

According to the scatter plots obtained, we can say that departure and arrival delays have a linear relationship. Most of the time, departure delays equivalently impacted the arrival time.

It is also worth noting that when plotted together, both earliness and tardiness minutes formed an almost perfect regression line. However, the linear model had a different slope on the earliness one when plotted separately.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

It was possible to get more insights using the relationship between the arrival and departure delay times. The regression plots helped us assume that each departure delay equivalently affects the arrival time. Moreover, the change in travel distance over the years shows the almost stable trends.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Observing the relationship between the travel distance and the air time also provided reasonable insights. It was possible to see that most of the flights were among shorter distances lasting for an average of about 200-300 minutes.

How does the average delay time vary along the scheduled arrival and departure hours?

In [33]:
from datetime import time

# custom function
def convert_datetime(str_time: float):
    if pd.isna(str_time):
        return
    str_time = str(round(str_time))
    if len(str_time) == 4:
        hour = str_time[:2]
        minutes = str_time[2:4]
        if int(hour) > 23:
            return np.nan
        hour_minute = time(hour=int(hour), minute=int(minutes))
    elif len(str_time) == 3:
        hour = str_time[:1]
        minutes = str_time[2:3]
        if int(hour) > 23:
            return np.nan
        hour_minute = time(hour=int(hour), minute=int(minutes))
    elif len(str_time) == 2:
        hour = str_time[0]
        minutes = str_time[1]
        if int(hour) > 23:
            return np.nan
        hour_minute = time(hour=int(hour), minute=int(minutes))
    else:
        hour_minute = np.nan
    return hour_minute

Observation¶

We can see from the line plot that both scheduled arrival and departure hours had similar values in regard to the average mean delay time. The delay minutes seemed to have increased during the later hours.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

We could get more insights regarding delay times using the specific hours of the day. Moreover, we could see a rather stable trend of average delay times in category-based analysis.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

It was interesting that the security issues were the least common for flight cancellation, however one of the reasons that make up the most delay occurrences.

Conclusions¶

One of the main focuses of the exploration was towards the flight delays and their relationships with other essential features.

When data was analysed in terms of delays, some flights had to be postponed for a couple of hours, while the most number of delays were for a minute. The most common reason for flight cancellation was carrier, the second most common being weather, followed by NAS, and only in a few cases security. Interestingly enough, security delay had the most number of occurrences, with about 10-20 minutes of tardiness while being the least common for flight cancellation.

In terms of relationships between arrival and departure delays, most of the time, departure delays equivalently impacted the arrival time. The average delay time of the flights among the categories almost remained stable during the period.

In many cases, the logarithmic scaling had to be performed due to the large number of outliers.
